# Hubert config for this repo

> This file lives at `.hubert/README.md` in the default branch
> of any repo Hubert watches. It is read by the orchestrator,
> the execution agent, and the reviewer agent on every run, so
> changes take effect immediately on the next orchestrator pass
> — no Hubert restart needed. The trusted-user list is NOT in
> this file; Hubert derives it from the repo's actual GitHub
> collaborators. See `SECURITY.md` in the Hubert repo for why.

## Build, test, lint

These are the commands the execution agent runs before opening
a PR, and that the reviewer agent runs before approving one.
**All of them must pass.** If a command isn't applicable, omit
it; do not stub it out with `true`.

```
build:    go build ./...
test:     go test ./...
lint:     golangci-lint run
```

## Cost caps

Per-issue and per-day caps in USD. The execution agent tracks
its spend against the per-issue cap and aborts before
exceeding it. `hubert-snap` sums per-repo daily totals from
`🤖 hubert-cost` comments; the orchestrator refuses to
dispatch new work once the per-day cap is hit (resets at UTC
midnight).

```
budget_per_issue_usd: 5
budget_per_day_usd:   50
```

The cost cap is a soft ceiling — because cost is reported
per-tool-call, a single expensive tool call can overshoot the
cap by one call's worth. When that happens, the next
orchestrator pass pivots to a cheaper backend (OpenCode free
pool) rather than retrying against the same provider.

## Pause and kill switch

Three granularities of stop:

- **Global:** the shared `hubert-config` kill-switch issue
  labeled `STOP` — Hubert across all watched repos goes
  quiet immediately.
- **Per-repo:** a `hubert-paused` label on this repo's
  kill-switch issue pauses Hubert for this repo only.
  Handy during migrations or incidents.
- **Per-issue:** a `hubert-paused` label on any individual
  issue pauses work on that issue without closing it.
  In-flight runs complete and lock cleanly; no new work
  dispatches until the label is removed.

The orchestrator workflow's first step checks all three
before spending any LLM tokens. Flip a label from your
phone.

## Merge style

How the reviewer agent should merge approved PRs. One of
`squash`, `merge`, `rebase`. Defaults to `squash` if omitted.

```
merge_style: squash
```

## Branch naming

The pattern Hubert uses when creating branches for new issues.
`{issue}` is the issue number; `{slug}` is a short kebab-case
slug derived from the issue title.

```
branch_pattern: hubert/issue-{issue}-{slug}
```

## Backend and model preference

Which LLM backends and models the orchestrator is allowed to
route this project's work to. The deployment image determines
which CLIs are installed; this config narrows the allowed set
further for privacy- or quality-sensitive projects.

If `allowed_backends` is omitted, the orchestrator may pick
any backend the image supports. If `default_model` is omitted,
the orchestrator picks per task. The orchestrator pass itself
always runs on `claude` regardless of this setting, since
planning quality matters and the pass is short.

```
allowed_backends: [claude, opencode]
default_model:    claude-opus-4-6
```

For example, a project that handles sensitive data might set
`allowed_backends: [claude]` to refuse routing to OpenCode's
free tier even when the orchestrator would otherwise pick it.
A cost-sensitive project with mechanical issues might set
`default_model: opencode/big-pickle` to bias cheaply.

## Notes for the agents

Free-form prose for the orchestrator, execution agent, and
reviewer agent to read as project-specific context. This is
where you put the "I care about X, please don't do Y, our
conventions are Z" guidance you would normally give a new
human contributor.

The original brief author has strong feelings about
correctness and completeness. Mention them here if your
project has similar standards. Mention any test or build
quirks the agents should know about ("the integration tests
take 20 minutes, plan accordingly", "lints fail if you don't
run `go generate ./...` first", etc.).

Example notes for a real project:

> - This is a Go monorepo with Flutter sub-projects under
>   `mobile/`. Most issues will be backend-only; if you find
>   yourself touching Flutter, escalate first.
> - Protobuf schemas are generated; never edit `*.pb.go` by
>   hand. Run `make proto` after editing `.proto` files.
> - The integration tests under `tests/integration/` need a
>   real Postgres; the unit tests don't. CI runs both.
> - This repo uses git submodules — the runner must
>   `git submodule update --init --recursive` before build.
> - We use Conventional Commits. Scope is the package name.
> - Don't add new dependencies without filing a separate
>   issue first; dep additions are a human review.

## Reserved for v2 (ignored by v1)

v1 silently ignores these so projects can prototype v2
features without breaking v1 parsing:

- **`.hubert/agents/*.md`** — per-project agent personas
  (frontend-developer, schema-migrator, security-auditor,
  etc.). v2 dispatches load the named persona file as
  role context on top of the embedded execution prompt.
  v1 ignores the directory.
- **Label → persona mapping** block in this README. The
  block shape is reserved; v1 doesn't parse it. Example
  of the intended v2 shape:

  ```
  persona_mapping:
    area:database: schema-migrator
    area:frontend: frontend-developer
    area:security: security-auditor
  ```

See PLAN.md §8 "v2: per-project agent personas" for the
full design.
